{
  "texts": [
    "For example, in the ASAP-AES dataset (see Sect. 6.1), essays are graded based on quality attributes such as content, organization, style, fluency and vocabulary usage (Hamner et al. 2012).",
    "In contrast, deep learning-based AES relies on the capability of neural network models to identify complex patterns in essays.",
    "These models demonstrate the ability to predict scores aligned with those of human graders.",
    "This has been showcased through various approaches, including simple deep learning models (Taghipour and Ng 2016; Alikaniotis et al. 2016; Dong and Zhang 2016; Dong et al. 2017; Cozma et al. 2018; Liang et al. 2018), trait-based neural models (Tay et al. 2018; Nadeem et al. 2019; Hussein et al. 2020; Song et al. 2020a; Kumar et al. 2021; He et al. 2022), transformer-based models (Yang et al. 2020; Cao et al. 2020; Wang et al. 2022b; Rodriguez et al. 2019; Han et al. 2023b; Xue et al. 2021), and cross-domain AES, which is particularly beneficial in scenarios with limited data in the target domain (Cozma et al. 2018; Dong and Zhang 2016; Jin et al. 2018; Cao et al. 2020; Ridley et al. 2020 Ridley et al., 2021;; Chen and Li 2023; Jiang et al. 2023; Do et al. 2023).",
    "Despite the existence of papers on essay score prediction and generalization, crucial aspects of writing evaluation, such as providing feedback, have often been overlooked."
  ]
}